    {
      "type": "answer",
      "text": "I can see you're getting a **WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR** BSOD. Let me research this and provide you with a comprehensive analysis.",
      "timestamp": 1783146240223
    },
    {
      "type": "thought",
      "text": "The user is showing a BSOD (Blue Screen of Death) with the stop code \"WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR\". They want me to:\n\n1. Investigate this using proper enterprise root cause analysis\n2. Tell them its \"fixibility score\" using \"ifix\" (probably iFixit repairability score concept)\n3. Tell them how reliable it is\n4. Whether they can improve PC temperature\n5. Check if components are okay\n6. They don't want to stress test components\n7. They want a decent assessment using PowerShell/Python tools\n\nHowever, I'm currently in \"Plan Mode\" - I cannot make any file edits or system changes. I can only observe, analyze, and plan. Let me provide analysis and recommendations.\n\nLet me analyze the WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR:\n\nThis error is related to hardware - specifically Windows Hardware Error Architecture. Common causes:\n- CPU overheating\n- CPU voltage issues (overclocking)\n- RAM failures\n- Hard drive/SSD issues\n- Motherboard issues\n- Power supply issues\n\nLet me search for more information and provide recommendations.",
      "timestamp": 1783146281466
    },
    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "websearch",
      "code": "{\"query\": \"WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR root cause analysis enterprise fix 2024 2025\"}",
      "output": "{\n  \"search_id\": \"search_f45f8fc74a3f4dea99fb59f9d0cc7b51\",\n  \"results\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.techbloat.com/whea-uncorrectable-error-troubleshooting-guide-for-2026.html\",\n      \"title\": \"WHEA Uncorrectable Error: Troubleshooting Guide for 2026\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2026-05-27\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"The timing matters because it can point toward a likely fault domain: crashes under heavy CPU load suggest thermals, voltage, CPU, RAM, or power delivery; crashes during GPU-heavy workloads suggest the graphics card, PCIe slot, GPU driver, or power supply; crashes during file transfers or boot may implicate an SSD, NVMe firmware, storage controller, or filesystem damage.\\n\\n### What “uncorrectable” really implies\\n\\nModern PCs can detect and sometimes recover from minor hardware errors. For example, memory with error correction can fix certain bit errors, and PCIe devices can retry some transactions. An “uncorrectable” WHEA event means the reported fault exceeded what the system could recover from safely. That may be a one-time instability event, but repeated WHEA crashes are a strong signal that something in the hardware, firmware, driver stack, cooling, or power configuration needs attention.\\n* **Single crash after a major change:** often worth investigating recent driver, BIOS, Windows, hardware, or overclocking changes first.\\n* **Repeated crashes under load:** commonly points to heat, voltage instability, RAM settings, GPU issues, or a weak power supply.\\n* **Crashes with disk errors:** may indicate SSD/HDD health problems, NVMe firmware issues, cabling, or storage controller faults.\\n* **Crashes after sleep or resume:** can involve BIOS power management, chipset drivers, GPU drivers, or device firmware.\\n\\nFor troubleshooting, treat WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR as a stability investigation rather than a generic Windows crash. The goal is to identify which layer reported the fault, what changed before the crashes began, and whether the problem follows a pattern. That approach helps separate a bad driver or firmware mismatch from a genuinely failing CPU, RAM module, SSD, graphics card, motherboard, or power supply.\\n\\n## Common Causes: Hardware, Drivers, BIOS, and Overclocking\\nThe WHEA Uncorrectable Error usually appears when Windows receives a severe hardware error report from the processor, chipset, memory controller, PCIe bus, storage controller, or another low-level component. In practice, the cause is not always a completely dead part. It can also be unstable firmware, a bad driver interacting with hardware, aggressive performance settings, overheating, or a power delivery problem that only shows up under load.\\n\\nBecause WHEA errors sit close to the hardware layer, they often happen during demanding tasks: gaming, compiling code, video rendering, running virtual machines, waking from sleep, installing updates, or transferring large files. A system may appear stable on the desktop but crash the moment the CPU boosts, the GPU draws more power, or the SSD controller is stressed. The minidump, Event Viewer entry, or stop code parameters can help narrow the suspect area, but the most common sources fall into a few categories.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://techlasi.com/pc/whea-uncorrectable-error-troubleshooting-guide\",\n      \"title\": \"WHEA Uncorrectable Error: Troubleshooting Guide for 2026\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2026-02-12\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"# WHEA Uncorrectable Error: Troubleshooting Guide for 2026\\n\\nBy [MK Usmaan](https://techlasi.com/author/mkusman22/ \\\"View all posts by MK Usmaan\\\") / February 12, 2026\\n\\nAre you facing the dreaded blue screen with a WHEA uncorrectable error message? You’re not alone. This frustrating hardware related error has troubled computer users for years, but with advances in diagnostic technology in 2026, we now have better solutions than ever before. This comprehensive guide will walk you through everything you need to know about WHEA errors, from understanding what they are to implementing the most effective fixes using the latest tools and techniques.\\n\\nWHEA Uncorrectable Error\\n\\n## **What is a WHEA Uncorrectable Error?**\\n\\nA WHEA (Windows Hardware Error Architecture) uncorrectable error occurs when Windows detects a serious hardware problem that it cannot recover from automatically.\\nUnlike correctable hardware errors that Windows can resolve on the fly, uncorrectable errors force your system to shut down to prevent potential damage to your hardware or data corruption.\\n\\n### **Windows Hardware Error Architecture**\\n\\nWindows Hardware Error Architecture is a platform level error handling mechanism introduced in [Windows Vista](https://techlasi.com/savvy/windows-vs-linux-vs-macos/) that provides a standardized way for the operating system to handle hardware errors. WHEA improves upon the older Machine Check Architecture by offering enhanced error reporting and more detailed diagnostic information.\\n\\nTable of Contents\\n\\n* What is a WHEA Uncorrectable Error?\\n  \\n    + Windows Hardware Error Architecture\\n    + Common Error Codes Associated with WHEA Errors\\n* Primary Causes of WHEA Uncorrectable Errors\\n  \\n    + Hardware Component Failures\\n    + Overclocking Issues\\n    + Driver and Firmware Problems\\n* Symptoms and Identification of WHEA Uncorrectable Errors\\n+ Blue Screen of Death (BSOD) Appearances\\n    + Event Viewer Diagnostics\\n* Step-by-Step Troubleshooting Guide\\n  \\n    + Immediate Actions to Take\\n    + Advanced Diagnostic Procedures\\n    + Hardware Component Verification\\n* Prevention Strategies for WHEA Errors\\n  \\n    + Proper System Maintenance\\n    + Cooling Solutions and Temperature Management\\n    + Safe Overclocking Practices\\n* Recent Developments in WHEA Error Management\\n  \\n    + Advanced Diagnostic Tools\\n    + AI Assisted Troubleshooting\\n* Conclusion\\n* FAQs\\n  \\n    + Can software cause WHEA uncorrectable errors?\\n    + How can I tell which hardware component is causing my WHEA error?\\n    + Are WHEA errors covered under warranty?\\n    + Can updating BIOS fix WHEA uncorrectable errors?\\n    + Why do WHEA errors sometimes occur only during specific activities like gaming?\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://umatechnology.org/whea-uncorrectable-error-troubleshooting-guide-for-2026\",\n      \"title\": \"WHEA Uncorrectable Error: Troubleshooting Guide for 2026\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2026-05-21\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Check the drive’s SMART health with the manufacturer’s tool, update SSD firmware, reseat the drive if it is removable, and make sure it has adequate cooling. Back up files immediately if the drive reports media errors, critical warnings, or rapid health decline.\\n\\n### Should I update my BIOS or UEFI to fix WHEA Uncorrectable Error?\\n\\nA BIOS/UEFI update can help if the problem is related to CPU microcode, memory compatibility, PCIe stability, or a newer processor installed on an older motherboard. Use the motherboard or laptop manufacturer’s exact model page, avoid beta firmware unless support recommends it, and do not interrupt the update. After updating, load optimized defaults before reapplying settings such as XMP, EXPO, undervolting, or fan curves.\\n\\n### Is it safe to keep using a PC that gets WHEA Uncorrectable Error?\\n\\nOccasional crashes after a bad driver or unstable tuning may not mean immediate hardware failure, but repeated WHEA errors should not be ignored.\\nContinued use can risk data loss if the cause is storage failure, overheating, or unstable power. Back up your data first, remove overclocks, monitor temperatures, and stop heavy workloads until the system passes stability tests.\\n\\n## Bottom Line\\n\\nThe WHEA Uncorrectable Error is usually a sign that Windows detected a serious hardware or low-level system stability problem, so the safest approach is to troubleshoot methodically: undo recent changes, check temperatures, update BIOS/UEFI and drivers, then test memory, storage, CPU, GPU, and power stability.\\n\\nIf the error continues after clean updates, safe settings, and component diagnostics, treat it as a likely failing part rather than a normal software crash. Back up data, stop overclocking, and consider professional testing or hardware replacement before the issue leads to data loss or an unbootable system.\\n\\n#### Quick Recap\\n\\nBestseller No. 1\\n\\n[Data Recovery software compatible with Windows 11, 10, 8.\\n1, 7 – recover deleted and lost files – rescue deleted images, photos, audios, videos, documents and more](https://www.amazon.com/dp/B09TL7K1TF?tag=umatechnology09-20&linkCode=ogi&th=1&psc=1&keywords=windows+recovery+software \\\"Data Recovery software compatible with Windows 11, 10, 8.1, 7 – recover deleted and lost files – rescue deleted images, photos, audios, videos, documents and more\\\")\\n\\n[Data Recovery software compatible with Windows 11, 10, 8.1, 7 – recover deleted and lost files – rescue deleted images, photos, audios, videos, documents and more](https://www.amazon.com/dp/B09TL7K1TF?tag=umatechnology09-20&linkCode=ogi&th=1&psc=1&keywords=windows+recovery+software \\\"Data Recovery software compatible with Windows 11, 10, 8.1, 7 – recover deleted and lost files – rescue deleted images, photos, audios, videos, documents and more\\\")\\n\\nData recovery software for retrieving lost files; Easily recover documents, audios, videos, photos, images and e-mails\\n\\n$24.99\\n\\nBestseller No.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.ninjaone.com/blog/how-to-fix-whea-uncorrectable-error-in-windows-11\",\n      \"title\": \"How to Fix \\\"WHEA_Uncorrectable_Error\\\" in Windows 11\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2026-02-24\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Home / Blog / IT Ops / How to Fix the WHEA\\\\_Uncorrectable\\\\_Error in Windows 11\\n\\nIT Ops\\n\\n/\\n\\n* Last updated February 24, 2026\\n\\n/\\n\\n* 6 min read\\n\\n# How to Fix the WHEA\\\\_Uncorrectable\\\\_Error in Windows 11\\n\\n* Picture of Mikhail Blacer Mikhail Blacer\\n\\nby Mikhail Blacer , IT Technical Writer\\n\\nHow to Fix the WHEA Uncorrectable Error in Windows 11 blog banner image\\n\\nTable of contents\\n\\n## Instant Summary\\n\\nSummarize Blog\\n\\nThis NinjaOne blog post offers a comprehensive basic CMD commands list and deep dive into Windows commands with over 70 essential cmd commands for both beginners and advanced users. It explains practical command prompt commands for file management, directory navigation, network troubleshooting, disk operations, and automation with real examples to improve productivity. Whether you’re learning foundational cmd commands or mastering advanced Windows CLI tools, this guide helps you use the Command Prompt more effectively.\\n\\nFree Trial\\n\\n## Key Points\\n* Identify Faulting Hardware: Review WHEA-Logger events in Event Viewer to isolate CPU, memory, PCIe bus, or storage errors.\\n* Update BIOS/UEFI Firmware First: Install vendor-supported firmware updates to fix instability from outdated microcode, voltage control, or PCIe initialization.\\n* Run Targeted Hardware Diagnostics: Stress-test RAM, CPU, and storage using vendor tools or industry-standard diagnostics to confirm whether components fail under load.\\n* Update Chipset, Storage, and Device Drivers: Install the latest supported drivers to correct hardware signaling issues that may trigger repeated WHEA events.\\n* Validate Post-Repair Stability: Clear WHEA logs, apply stress tests, and monitor Event Viewer to ensure the system remains stable without recurring hardware faults.\\n\\nA WHEA (Windows Hardware Error Architecture) Uncorrectable Error (or **whea\\\\_uncorrectable\\\\_error** ) occurs when hardware reports a fault via the WHEA system.\\nIt’s known as a blue screen of death (BSOD) error that comes from failing CPUs, unstable memory, PCIe bus issues, storage faults, or outdated firmware.\\n\\nThis guide delivers a workflow to fix a WHEA Uncorrectable Error. We’ll go through ways on how to identify the hardware source, run targeted diagnostics, update firmware, remove overclocking, and verify system stability.\\n\\n## Steps to fix the WHEA uncorrectable error\\n\\nTo stop the [WHEA uncorrectable error code](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/drivers/whea/introduction-to-the-windows-hardware-error-architecture) , you will need to perform hardware-focused troubleshooting. Before you go through the steps, you will need to confirm the following requirements:\\n\\n📌 **Prerequisites:**\\n\\n* You will need administrator access on the affected device.\\n* This requires you to enter BIOS or UEFI for firmware and stability changes.\\n* You will need to have tools for memory, CPU, and storage diagnostics.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://linustechtips.com/topic/1440210-whea-uncorrectable-error\",\n      \"title\": \"Whea Uncorrectable Error - Troubleshooting - Linus Tech Tips\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2022-07-01\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"com%2Ftopic%2F1440210-whea-uncorrectable-error%2F%3Fdo%3DfindComment%26comment%3D15459738&title=Whea+Uncorrectable+Error \\\"Share on Reddit\\\")\\n\\n* * *\\n\\nMore sharing options...\\n\\n- [](https://linustechtips.com/profile/313534-windows7ge/ \\\"Go to Windows7ge's profile\\\") [](https://linustechtips.com/profile/313534-windows7ge/badges/)\\n* ### **[Windows7ge](https://linustechtips.com/profile/313534-windows7ge/ \\\"Go to Windows7ge's profile\\\")**\\n* Member\\n* Writer of Guides & Tutorials\\n    + [12\\\\.3k](https://linustechtips.com/profile/313534-windows7ge/content/ \\\"12,308 posts\\\")\\n    + [255](https://linustechtips.com/profile/313534-windows7ge/solutions/ \\\"255 solutions\\\")\\n\\n[](https://linustechtips.com/index.php?app=awards&module=awards&controller=awards&do=info&award=4773) [](https://www.boincstats.com/stats/-1/user/detail/73865194514/overview)\\n\\n[](https://linustechtips.com/index.php?app=awards&module=awards&controller=awards&do=info&award=7093)\\n\\n[](https://linustechtips.com/index.php?\\napp=awards&module=awards&controller=awards&do=info&award=7229) [](https://folding.extremeoverclocking.com/user_summary.php?s=&u=1294415)\\n\\n[](https://linustechtips.com/index.php?app=awards&module=awards&controller=awards&do=info&award=7560)\\n\\n[Posted June 29, 2022](https://linustechtips.com/topic/1440210-whea-uncorrectable-error/?do=findComment&comment=15459750)\\n\\n* [](https://linustechtips.com/topic/1440210-whea-uncorrectable-error/ \\\"Share this post\\\")\\n\\nUsually WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR is associated with a hardware failure. This could be an issue with your PSU, GPU, Motherboard, etc.\\n\\nJust from my experience dealing with this error in the past I'd try a different PSU first but you can try pulling sticks of RAM if you want to test something easier. I wouldn't put my trust in whatever Windows memory check is. Most people use MemTestx86 for memory testing and even then there's no guarantee the memory error will propagate on the first go around.\\nMultiple runs might be required so I'll often just pull a stick at a time and see if the system becomes stable again. Faster. Just as easy.\\n\\n**Guides & Tutorials:**\\n\\n[PROXMOX - Rebuilding ZFS RAID rpool After Disk Failure](https://linustechtips.com/topic/1535985-proxmox-rebuilding-zfs-raid-rpool-after-disk-failure/)\\n\\n[Mass Deploying Customized Windows 10/11 Installs](https://linustechtips.com/topic/1531766-mass-deploying-customized-windows-1011-installs/)\\n\\n[Building a GNU/Linux Based Windows Deployment Server](https://linustechtips.com/topic/1482112-building-a-gnulinux-based-windows-deployment-server/)\\n\\n[GNU/Linux Installer Server: Installation & Configuration](https://linustechtips.com/topic/1445036-gnulinux-installer-server-installation-configuration/)\\n\\n[How to: Use (i)PXE to Install Windows from a Network](https://linustechtips.com/topic/1441143-how-to-use-ipxe-to-install-windows-from-a-network/)\\n\\n[Why Memorize IP's When You Can Self-Host DNS Instead?](https://linustechtips.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://support.microsoft.com/en-US/Windows/experience/performance-optimization/how-to-fix-whea-uncorrectable-error\",\n      \"title\": \"How to fix WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR | Microsoft Support\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"How to fix WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR | Microsoft Support\\nHow to attempt to fix the blue screen/stop error WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR by using Windows Update, manually updating drivers, using system recovery/repair, or troubleshooting the blue screen/stop error.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://couldask.com/en/guides/tech/oswindows/how-to-fix-whea-uncorrectable-error\",\n      \"title\": \"How to Fix WHEA Uncorrectable Error in Windows 10/11\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Sunday, June 28\\n\\nTheme\\n\\nEN ▾\\n\\n[Русский](https://couldask.com/ru/kak-ispravit-oshibku-whea-uncorrectable-error) [English](https://couldask.com/en/how-to-fix-whea-uncorrectable-error)\\n\\n🏠 Home Sections: All 📖 Guides 🔧 Fixes 💡 Concepts ⚖️ Compare 🛠️ Tools Справка\\n\\n×\\n\\n#### Help\\n\\nUse the search bar to find error codes or manuals. Articles are categorized in the top menu.\\n\\nSubcategories: Back All Adults Contact Excel Git Google Mail Media Windows More 7 ▾\\n\\n### Select Subcategory\\n\\n×\\n\\nHome / Guides / IT & Tech / Windows\\n\\nIT & Tech\\n\\n# How to Fix WHEA Uncorrectable Error in Windows 10/11\\n\\nCouldAsk Editorial 27\\\\.06.2026 2 min 👁️ 139\\n\\nQuick Solution\\n\\nError 0x00000124 is a critical hardware failure (overheating, overclocking, or power issues). Key steps: reset BIOS to factory defaults, disable overclocking, and check system files and disk integrity.\\nBlue screen of death with WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR and stop code 0x00000124 on a computer monitor The **WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR** (stop code `0x00000124` ) is a critical failure of the Windows Hardware Error Architecture. Unlike many other Blue Screen of Death (BSoD) errors, this one indicates a hardware issue in 90% of cases, rather than a software glitch.\\n\\n## Main Causes of the Error\\n\\nThe system protects itself to prevent physical damage to the components. The primary culprits are:\\n\\n* Overheating of the processor (CPU) or graphics card (GPU).\\n* Unstable overclocking or enabled XMP profiles for RAM.\\n* A faulty power supply unit (PSU) causing voltage spikes.\\n* Physical wear and tear of the system drive (SSD/HDD).\\n\\n## Step-by-Step Solution\\n\\n### Step 1: Disable Overclocking\\n\\nIf you have overclocked your CPU or RAM, revert to the base settings.\\n1\\\\. Restart your computer and enter the BIOS/UEFI (usually by pressing `Del` or `F2` ).\\n2\\\\.\\nFind the **Load Optimized Defaults** option or manually reset the CPU and RAM frequency settings (disable XMP).\\n3\\\\. Save the changes ( `F10` ) and reboot.\\n\\n⚠️ Before updating or resetting the BIOS, ensure your computer is connected to a reliable power source (ideally through a UPS). A sudden power outage while working in the BIOS can brick your motherboard.\\n\\n### Step 2: Check System Files and Disk\\n\\nIf the BIOS is reset but the error persists, check the integrity of the file system.\\nOpen the Command Prompt as an Administrator and type the following commands one by one:\\n\\n* `chkdsk /f /r` (requires a reboot to scan the disk).\\n* `sfc /scannow` (system file check).\\n\\nℹ️ Pro Tip\\n\\nThe WHEA error often occurs after installing new RAM sticks. If you recently upgraded your memory, try removing the modules, wiping the contacts with a regular eraser, and pushing them back in until you hear a distinct click.\\n\\n## Recommended Reading\\n\\nFor an in-depth analysis of BSoD causes, I recommend studying:\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.windowsmode.com/fix-whea-uncorrectable-error-windows\",\n      \"title\": \"How to Fix WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR in Windows 10/11 - Windows Mode\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2026-05-15\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Most people solve it by Fix 2 or Fix 3. If your PC is overclocked, start with Fix 1 first.\\n\\nWhat This Error Means at a Glance\\n\\n* Windows detected an unrecoverable hardware error and forced a restart.\\n* Most common causes: overclocking, faulty RAM, bad device driver, or overheating CPU.\\n* Less common causes: failing hard drive or SSD, corrupted system files, bad Windows update.\\n* This is a hardware-level crash, not a typical app or software error.\\n* Affects Windows 10 and Windows 11. More common on overclocked or custom-built PCs.\\n\\nError Type\\n\\nBSOD / Hardware\\n\\nRoot Cause\\n\\nCPU / RAM / Driver\\n\\nAffects\\n\\nWindows 10 / 11\\n\\nDifficulty\\n\\nBeginner to advanced\\n\\nTime to Fix\\n\\n10 min – several hours\\n\\nTable of Contents\\n\\n* Video: How to Fix WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR on Windows\\n* What Causes WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR?\\n* How to Fix WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR\\n* Quick Checklist: What to Try First\\n* Still Getting WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR? Advanced Steps\\n* Frequently Asked Questions\\n* Related Windows Error Fixes\\n\\n## Video: How to Fix WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR on Windows\\n\\nWatch the full fix walkthrough for WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR on Windows 10 and 11, covering the overclocking reset, driver update, RAM test, and SFC repair steps shown below.\\n\\n## What Causes WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR?\\n\\nThis error has more possible causes than most blue screens. Check the list below and pick the fix that best matches your situation before working through the numbered steps.\\n\\nOverclocking (Most Common)\\n\\nRunning your CPU, RAM, or GPU faster than stock speeds puts extra stress on the hardware. Even a previously stable overclock can cause this error after a Windows update, temperature spike, or power fluctuation.\\n\\nFaulty or Incompatible RAM\\n\\nBad memory is one of the top hardware causes. This includes physically failing RAM sticks, RAM running at the wrong speed for your motherboard, or mismatched sticks that are not compatible with each other.\\n\\nBad or Outdated Drivers\\nGPU drivers, chipset drivers, and storage controller drivers are the most common driver culprits. A buggy driver update can trigger this error even on hardware that was working fine the day before.\\n\\nOverheating CPU or GPU\\n\\nWhen a processor gets too hot, it can trigger hardware-level errors that cause this blue screen. Common on laptops with blocked vents, desktops with dried-out thermal paste, or rigs running demanding workloads in a hot room.\\n\\nFailing Hard Drive or SSD\\n\\nA drive that is starting to fail can trigger hardware errors as Windows tries to read or write to bad sectors. This is more common on older HDDs but can also happen with SSDs that are near end of life.\\n\\nCorrupted System Files\\n\\nA failed Windows update, a sudden shutdown during an update, or malware can corrupt core Windows files. This is less common than hardware causes but worth checking if all hardware tests come back clean.\\n\\n## How to Fix WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR\\n\\nWork through these fixes in order.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.positioniseverything.net/whea-uncorrectable-error-troubleshooting-guide-for-2026\",\n      \"title\": \"WHEA Uncorrectable Error: Troubleshooting Guide for 2026\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"* What the WHEA Uncorrectable Error Means in Windows\\n  \\n    + Where Windows records more detail\\n* Common Causes: Hardware Failure, Drivers, Overclocking, and Firmware\\n  \\n    + Hardware problems\\n    + Driver and Windows-level causes\\n    + Overclocking and aggressive performance settings\\n    + BIOS, UEFI, and firmware issues\\n* First Checks Before Advanced Troubleshooting\\n  \\n    + Record the stop code details and recent changes\\n    + Remove overclocks and performance tuning\\n    + Check physical connections, cooling, and power\\n* How to Diagnose CPU, RAM, GPU, and Storage Problems\\n  \\n    + CPU and motherboard checks\\n    + RAM testing\\n    + GPU and power-related testing\\n    + Storage and file system checks\\n* Driver, BIOS, and Windows Update Fixes\\n  \\n    + Update chipset, storage, GPU, and network drivers carefully\\n    + Check BIOS/UEFI updates and reset unstable firmware settings\\n    + Use Windows Update, optional updates, and system file repair\\n* When to Reset Settings, Replace Hardware, or Seek Repair\\n  \\n    + Reset firmware and performance settings first\\n    + Replace parts when failures follow the component\\n* Frequently Asked Questions\\n  \\n    + Can the WHEA Uncorrectable Error be caused by software, or is it always bad hardware?\\n    + What should I check first after getting a WHEA Uncorrectable Error?\\n    + How do I know whether RAM, CPU, GPU, or storage is causing the crash?\\n    + Can XMP, EXPO, undervolting, or overclocking cause WHEA errors?\\n    + When should I replace hardware or take the PC to a repair shop?\\n* Bottom Line\\n\\n## What the WHEA Uncorrectable Error Means in Windows\\n\\nThe WHEA Uncorrectable Error is a Windows blue screen stop error usually shown with the code **WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR** .\\nWHEA stands for **Windows Hardware Error Architecture** , the part of Windows that receives, records, and reports serious hardware-related errors from the processor, motherboard firmware, chipset, memory controller, PCIe devices, storage controller, and other low-level components. When Windows displays this error, it means the system detected a fault that it could not safely correct while the computer was running.\\n\\nThis crash is different from many ordinary application or driver failures. A typical app crash may close one program, and a typical driver bug may point clearly to a specific software file. A WHEA error often comes from below that layer: unstable CPU operation, faulty RAM, a failing NVMe SSD, PCIe communication errors, overheating, power delivery problems, firmware bugs, or aggressive BIOS settings. Windows stops the system because continuing could corrupt data, damage an open file system transaction, or allow the machine to keep running in an unreliable state.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.fastsoftwares.com/blog/whea-uncorrectable-error\",\n      \"title\": \"Fixing WHEA UNCORRECTABLE ERROR: Expert Solutions fastsoftwares.com https://www.fastsoftwares.com › ...\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2024-05-06\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Skip to navigation Skip to content\\n\\n#### Browse\\n\\n* [My Account](https://www.fastsoftwares.com//my-account/)\\n* [Customer Help](https://www.fastsoftwares.com/help-center-3/)\\n\\n#### Got questions?\\n\\n[Email us: [email protected]](#)\\n\\n[Home](https://www.fastsoftwares.com) / [Blog](https://www.fastsoftwares.com/category/blog/) / Fixing WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR: Expert Solutions\\n\\n# **How Do I Fix WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR?**\\n\\nfastsoftwares how to fix whea uncorrectable error 01\\n\\nWHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR, also known as a “blue screen of death” (BSOD), is a serious error that occurs on Windows computers, indicating that a hardware problem has occurred and the system has been shut down to prevent further damage. If you’re dealing with this error, it can be a frustrating experience, and you may feel like giving up on your computer. But don’t despair!\\n\\nYou can solve the issue and get your computer operating again by following a few simple steps.\\nTo get you back to your work or leisure activities as soon as possible, we will show you the best options to fix the WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR in this guide. To resolve this issue, we will go over all the necessary details.\\n\\nIf you want to put an end to the frustration caused by this error, keep reading!\\n\\n## **What Is the WHEA Uncorrectable Error?**\\n\\nThis error, also known as stop code WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR or Windows code 0x0000124, is a hardware error. It indicates an issue with your computer’s hardware, such as your GPU, CPU, or RAM. The WHEA Uncorrectable Error message is also caused by voltage issues.\\n\\nThe most common causes for WHEA Uncorrectable Error are:\\n\\n* Malfunctioning hardware\\n* Driver compatibility problems\\n* Overclocking and overheating\\n* Corrupt system files or registry keys\\n* Voltage changes and issues\\n\\nBecause this error is hard to diagnose accurately, we recommend that you take a look at the automatically generated error dump file (.\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"warnings\": null,\n  \"usage\": [\n    {\n      \"name\": \"sku_search\",\n      \"count\": 1\n    }\n  ],\n  \"session_id\": \"ses_0d4353dccffeI9tkgNAMHqAo4e\"\n}",
