    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "websearch",
      "code": "{\"query\": \"PowerShell Python tools check PC temperature WHEA error diagnostics 2024 2025\"}",
      "output": "{\n  \"search_id\": \"search_4b60d4f025db45df93617581be328de4\",\n  \"results\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.positioniseverything.net/whea-uncorrectable-error-troubleshooting-guide-for-2026\",\n      \"title\": \"WHEA Uncorrectable Error: Troubleshooting Guide for 2026\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2026-05-17\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"+ [CPU](https://www.positioniseverything.net/category/hardware/cpu/)\\n  \\n    + [Outlook](https://www.positioniseverything.net/category/microsoft-office/outlook/)\\n    + [Powerpoint](https://www.positioniseverything.net/category/microsoft-office/powerpoint/)\\n\\nSearch for:\\n\\nCategory [Blog](https://www.positioniseverything.net/category/blog/)\\n\\n# WHEA Uncorrectable Error: Troubleshooting Guide for 2026\\n\\nBy [positioniseverything](https://www.positioniseverything.net/author/positioniseverything/) Published May 17, 2026 21 min read\\n\\n* Author\\n* Recent Posts\\n\\n[](https://www.positioniseverything.net/author/positioniseverything/ \\\"positioniseverything\\\")\\n\\n[positioniseverything](https://www.positioniseverything.net/author/positioniseverything/)\\n\\n[](https://www.positioniseverything.net/author/positioniseverything/ \\\"positioniseverything\\\")\\n\\nLatest posts by positioniseverything ( [see all](https://www.positioniseverything.net/author/positioniseverything/) )\\nThe WHEA Uncorrectable Error is one of the more serious Windows blue screen errors because it usually points to a low-level hardware, firmware, or driver problem rather than a simple app crash. It can appear during gaming, startup, heavy workloads, Windows updates, or even while the PC is idle, often with little warning beyond a sudden restart and a stop code.\\n\\nIn 2026, the safest way to handle this error is to diagnose it methodically: check temperatures and power stability, remove unstable overclocks, test RAM and storage, review CPU and GPU behavior, update drivers, and verify BIOS/UEFI settings before replacing parts. A careful approach helps separate a temporary configuration issue from signs of failing hardware.\\n\\n[Guide Helped? Tip Us](https://ko-fi.com/yorkermedia) ×\\n\\n|\\\\# |Preview |Product |Price | |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n|1 |[Anker USB C Hub, 7in1 Multi-Port USB Adapter for Laptop/Mac, 4K@60Hz USB C to HDMI Splitter, 85W Max PD, 2 USB 3.\\n0 & 1 USBC Data Ports, SD/TF Card Reader, for Type C Devices (Charger Not Included)](https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0DXJQT19B?tag=positioniseverything-20&linkCode=ogi&th=1&psc=1&keywords=usb+c+accessories \\\"Anker USB C Hub, 7in1 Multi-Port USB Adapter for Laptop/Mac, 4K@60Hz USB C to HDMI Splitter, 85W Max PD, 2 USB 3.0 & 1 USBC Data Ports, SD/TF Card Reader, for Type C Devices (Charger Not Included)\\\") |[Anker USB C Hub, 7in1 Multi-Port USB Adapter for Laptop/Mac, 4K@60Hz USB C to HDMI Splitter, 85W Max...](https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0DXJQT19B?tag=positioniseverything-20&linkCode=ogi&th=1&psc=1&keywords=usb+c+accessories \\\"Anker USB C Hub, 7in1 Multi-Port USB Adapter for Laptop/Mac, 4K@60Hz USB C to HDMI Splitter, 85W Max PD, 2 USB 3.0 & 1 USBC Data Ports, SD/TF Card Reader, for Type C Devices (Charger Not Included)\\\") |$25.99 |[Buy on Amazon](https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0DXJQT19B?tag=positioniseverything-20&linkCode=ogi&th=1&psc=1&keywords=usb+c+accessories \\\"Buy on Amazon\\\") |\\n\\n...\\n\\nRun a memory test for RAM, check drive health with SMART data and the manufacturer’s diagnostic tool, stress-test the CPU while watching temperatures, and test the GPU separately with a graphics benchmark or stress tool. If crashes happen only under a specific workload, such as gaming, file transfers, or CPU rendering, that pattern can point to the failing component.\\n\\n### Can XMP, EXPO, undervolting, or overclocking cause WHEA errors?\\n\\nYes, unstable CPU, RAM, or GPU tuning is one of the most common causes of WHEA crashes, even if the system seemed stable before. Disable XMP/EXPO, remove undervolts, return clock speeds and voltages to stock, and test again for several days. If the error disappears, re-enable settings gradually or use a less aggressive memory speed or voltage profile.\\n\\n### When should I replace hardware or take the PC to a repair shop?\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://umatechnology.org/whea-uncorrectable-error-troubleshooting-guide-for-2026\",\n      \"title\": \"WHEA Uncorrectable Error: Troubleshooting Guide for 2026\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2026-05-21\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"For desktops, turn off the PC, switch off the PSU, unplug the power cord, and press the power button once to discharge residual power. Then check that the 24-pin motherboard cable, CPU EPS power cable, GPU power connectors, SATA data cables, and SSD connections are firmly seated. If the PC was moved recently, reseat the RAM and GPU. For modular power supplies, check the PSU-side connectors too. Avoid mixing modular PSU cables from another power supply, even if they appear to fit.\\n\\n|Quick check |What to look for |\\n| --- | --- |\\n|Event Viewer |Open Windows Logs > System and look for WHEA-Logger entries near the crash time. |\\n|Reliability Monitor |Search for “Reliability history” and review failed updates, driver crashes, and hardware errors. |\\n|Windows Update history |Check whether crashes began after a cumulative update, driver update, or firmware package. |\\n|Device Manager |Look for warning icons, unknown devices, or recently changed storage, GPU, chipset, and network drivers. |\\nAlso give the system a simple thermal inspection. Make sure vents are not blocked, fans spin normally, and dust is not packed into the CPU cooler, GPU heatsink, laptop exhaust, or power supply intake. If the PC crashes soon after launching a demanding app, leave the side panel on for normal airflow and monitor temperatures with a trusted tool. Do not start by deleting random drivers, editing the registry, or disabling security features. If these initial checks reveal a clear trigger, fix that item first; if not, move on to targeted driver, firmware, memory, storage, and stress testing.\\n\\n## Update or Roll Back Drivers, Windows, and BIOS/UEFI\\n\\nAfter the basic checks, focus on software and firmware changes that affect hardware communication. A WHEA Uncorrectable Error often appears when Windows receives a low-level hardware fault from the CPU, PCIe bus, memory controller, storage controller, or graphics device.\\nFaulty drivers, unstable chipset packages, a problematic Windows update, or outdated BIOS/UEFI firmware can all trigger or expose these errors. Work in a controlled order: change one thing, test the system, then move to the next item.\\n\\n### Update core drivers from trusted sources\\n\\nStart with drivers that sit closest to the hardware. For desktop PCs, use the motherboard manufacturer’s support page for the exact board model. For laptops and prebuilt systems, use the support page for the exact device model or service tag. Install the latest stable versions of the chipset driver, storage controller driver, network driver, and integrated device drivers. For graphics, use NVIDIA, AMD, or Intel directly unless the laptop vendor provides a customized package required for switchable graphics.\\n\\n##### Rank #3\\n\\n[AOMEI Backupper PRO - Backup software, recovery in case of malware infection, hard drive failure, or Windows crashes — for 2 PCs, lifetime license for Win 11 and 10](https://www.amazon.\\n\\n...\\n\\nRun tests one category at a time, record the results, and avoid changing several settings between tests, otherwise it becomes harder to identify the failing part.\\n\\n### Check memory stability first\\n\\nFaulty or unstable RAM can produce random crashes, corrupted files, app failures, and WHEA blue screens under load. Start with Windows Memory Diagnostic by searching for it from the Start menu and choosing a restart test. For a deeper check, use a bootable memory tester and let it complete mulle passes, especially if the crash happens only during gaming, rendering, compiling, or virtual machine work. If errors appear, power off the PC and reseat the RAM modules. Test one stick at a time in the motherboard slot recommended by the manual. If errors follow one module, replace that module. If errors happen only with XMP, EXPO, or high-speed memory profi\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/whea/?view=windowsserver2025-ps\",\n      \"title\": \"Whea module | Microsoft Learn\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"+ ShieldedVMDataFile\\n    + ShieldedVMProvisioning\\n    + ShieldedVMTemplate\\n    + SmbShare\\n    + SmbWitness\\n    + SMISConfig\\n    + SoftwareInventoryLogging\\n    + StartLayout\\n    + Storage\\n    + StorageBusCache\\n    + StorageMigrationService\\n    + StorageQoS\\n    + StorageReplica\\n    + SyncShare\\n    + SystemInsights\\n    + TLS\\n    + TroubleshootingPack\\n    + TrustedPlatformModule\\n    + UEV\\n    + UpdateServices\\n    + UserAccessLogging\\n    + VAMT\\n    + VMDirectStorage\\n    + VpnClient\\n    + Wdac\\n    + WDS\\n    + WebAdministration\\n    + WebApplicationProxy\\n    + Whea\\n        \\n        - [Commands](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/whea/?view=windowsserver2025-ps)\\n        - [Get-WheaMemoryPolicy](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/whea/get-wheamemorypolicy?view=windowsserver2025-ps)\\n        - [Set-WheaMemoryPolicy](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/whea/set-wheamemorypolicy?view=windowsserver2025-ps)\\n    + WindowsDeveloperLicense\\n+ WindowsDiagnosticData\\n    + WindowsErrorReporting\\n    + WindowsSearch\\n    + WindowsServerBackup\\n    + WindowsUpdate\\n    + WinHttpProxy\\n\\nDownload PDF\\n\\nTable of contents Exit editor mode\\n\\n1. [Learn](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/?view=windowsserver2025-ps)\\n2. [Windows](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/?view=windowsserver2025-ps)\\n3. [PowerShell](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module?view=windowsserver2025-ps)\\n\\nAsk Learn Ask Learn\\n\\n* * *\\n\\nNote\\n\\nAccess to this page requires authorization. You can try signing in or changing directories .\\n\\nAccess to this page requires authorization. You can try changing directories .\\n\\n# Whea module\\n\\nThis reference provides cmdlet descriptions and syntax for all Windows Hardware Error Architecture\\n(WHEA) cmdlets. It lists the cmdlets in alphabetical order based on the verb at the beginning of the\\ncmdlet.\\n\\n## Whea cmdlets\\n\\nExpand table\\n\\n|Cmdlet |Description |\\n| --- | --- |\\n|[Get-WheaMemoryPolicy](https://learn.microsoft.\\ncom/en-us/powershell/module/whea/get-wheamemorypolicy?view=windowsserver2025-ps) |Gets the WHEA memory policies for a computer. |\\n|[Set-WheaMemoryPolicy](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/whea/set-wheamemorypolicy?view=windowsserver2025-ps) |Sets the WHEA memory policy for a computer. |\\n\\n* * *\\n\\n## Feedback\\n\\nWas this page helpful?\\n\\nYes No\\n\\n### In this article\\n\\nWas this page helpful?\\n\\n## Ask Learn\\n\\nPreview\\n\\nAsk Learn is an AI assistant that can answer questions, clarify concepts, and define terms using trusted Microsoft documentation.\\n\\nEnglish (United States)\\n\\n[Your Privacy Choices](https://aka.ms/yourcaliforniaprivacychoices)\\n\\nTheme\\n\\n* Light\\n* Dark\\n* High contrast\\n\\n* [AI Disclaimer](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/principles-for-ai-generated-content)\\n* [Previous Versions](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/)\\n* [Blog](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-learn-blog/bg-p/MicrosoftLearnBlog)\\n* [Contribute](https://learn.microsoft.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://grokipedia.com/page/windows_hardware_error_architecture\",\n      \"title\": \"Windows Hardware Error Architecture — Grokipedia\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2026-01-11\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"These changes built on the foundational PCIe Advanced Error Reporting (AER) support from Vista, enabling more robust handling of PCIe-related corrected and uncorrected errors across the subsystem. [[[7]]()]() In Windows 8 and 8.1, WHEA focused on improving administrative and programmatic control over error policies, introducing the WMI provider class WHEAPolicyManagementMethods for dynamic policy configuration. Administrators could now manage WHEA policies—such as logging thresholds and recovery actions—either via this WMI class or the new WHEA PowerShell module, with changes taking immediate effect without requiring a system reboot. The legacy WMI method WHEAErrorSourceMethods::SetErrorSourceInfoRtn was deprecated in favor of these modern interfaces, streamlining error source management. [[[4]]()]() Windows 10 and 11 further evolved WHEA with emphases on developer usability, telemetry integration, and adaptation to emerging hardware standards.\\nStarting with Windows 10 version 2004, a version 2 (v2) interface simplified error source registration and reporting for device drivers, using structures like WHEA\\\\_ERROR\\\\_SOURCE\\\\_CONFIGURATION\\\\_DEVICE\\\\_DRIVER and APIs such as WheaAddErrorSourceDeviceDriver for streamlined integration; this reduced complexity for reporting errors from peripherals like GPUs and storage controllers. Enhanced Non-Maskable Interrupt (NMI) handling improved responsiveness to critical hardware faults. WHEA events became integral to Windows diagnostic telemetry, capturing detailed error records (e.g., via events like WheaProvider.WheaErrorRecord) including timestamps, severity levels, and binary payloads for cloud-based analysis; this data helps Microsoft refine updates, stability, and resilience. As of 2024, WHEA continues to support reliability in modern systems through these telemetry and interface improvements across Windows 10 and 11 updates. [[[8]]()]() [[[9]]()]()\\n\\n## Core Components\\n### Error Sources and Detection\\n\\nThe Windows Hardware Error Architecture (WHEA) identifies and responds to hardware malfunctions originating from various components in a computer system. These error sources encompass processors, memory subsystems, I/O devices, firmware interfaces, and platform-level hardware, each equipped with mechanisms to detect and signal anomalies. Detection primarily occurs through hardware-initiated notifications or periodic checks, enabling the operating system to address issues before they escalate. [[[10]]()]() Processor errors, a primary source, are detected via machine-check exceptions (MC#), which alert the operating system to internal faults such as arithmetic errors, bus protocol violations, or issues in the cache hierarchy. In multi-socket systems, these can include coherence errors across shared caches, where inconsistencies in data synchronization between processors trigger the exception.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://techlasi.com/pc/whea-uncorrectable-error-troubleshooting-guide\",\n      \"title\": \"WHEA Uncorrectable Error: Troubleshooting Guide for 2026\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2026-02-12\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"+ For CPUs: Consider AIO (All-In-One) liquid coolers with at least 240mm radiators for high performance processors\\n    + For GPUs: Undervolt using manufacturer utilities to reduce heat without sacrificing performance\\n    + For cases: Mesh-front cases with unobstructed airflow demonstrate 8-12°C lower internal temperatures in recent benchmarks\\n4. **Fan Curve Optimization** : Use motherboard utilities to create custom fan curves that balance noise and cooling performance based on temperature thresholds.\\n\\n### **Safe Overclocking Practices**\\n\\nIf you must overclock:\\n\\n1. **Incremental Adjustments** : Increase clock speeds in small increments (100MHz for CPU, 50MHz for GPU) and thoroughly test stability after each change.\\n2. **Voltage Limits** : Stay within safe voltage ranges for your specific hardware (consult manufacturer guidelines).\\n3. **Stress Testing Protocol** : Establish a testing regimen that includes:\\n   \\n    + Short high intensity tests (OCCT, Prime95)\\n+ Overnight stability verification\\n4. **Temperature Monitoring** : Set up alerts for when components exceed safe temperature thresholds.\\n5. **AI Assisted Overclocking** : Take advantage of the new Neural OC tools released in 2026 that can automatically find the optimal balance between performance and stability.\\n\\n## **Recent Developments in WHEA Error Management**\\n\\nThe tech industry has made significant strides in addressing hardware errors more effectively in recent years.\\n\\n[See also PC Health Check: How to Check Your Computer's Health in 2026](https://techlasi.com/pc/pc-health-check-how-to-check-your-computers-health/)\\n\\n### **Advanced Diagnostic Tools**\\n\\nNew diagnostic capabilities have emerged:\\n\\n1. **Enhanced Event Logging** : Windows 11’s latest updates provide more detailed hardware error information, including specific component failure predictions.\\n2.\\n**Hardware Error Pattern Recognition** : New monitoring tools can identify patterns in minor correctable errors that often precede major uncorrectable errors.\\n3. **Integrated Hardware Diagnostics** : Motherboard manufacturers now include comprehensive diagnostic tools directly in the UEFI interface, accessible before Windows loads.\\n4. **Component Specific Testing** : Specialized tools that can isolate and test individual subcomponents within larger hardware systems (like specific memory channels or CPU cores).\\n\\n### **AI Assisted Troubleshooting**\\n\\nArtificial intelligence has revolutionized hardware problem diagnosis:\\n\\n1. **Predictive Failure Analysis** : AI algorithms can now detect subtle signs of impending hardware failure days or weeks before catastrophic errors occur.\\n2. **Automated Diagnosis** : Several major PC manufacturers have introduced AI troubleshooting assistants that can guide users through diagnostic procedures specific to their exact hardware configuration.\\n3.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://expertbeacon.com/check-the-temperature-of-your-cpu-using-python-and-other-cool-tricks/\",\n      \"title\": \"Check The Temperature Of Your CPU Using Python (and Other Cool Tricks) - ExpertBeacon\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2024-09-07\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Check the temperature of your CPU using Python (and other cool tricks)\\n\\n[Coding](https://expertbeacon.com/tech-tutorial-tips/code/)\\n\\n# Check the temperature of your CPU using Python (and other cool tricks)\\n\\nBy Alex Mitchell Last Update on September 7, 2024\\n\\nComputer motherboard with CPU\\n\\nPython is an incredibly versatile programming language used for everything from web development and data analysis to machine learning and scientific computing. One lesser known capability of Python is that it allows you to monitor and manage various aspects of your computer‘s hardware through code.\\n\\nIn this comprehensive guide, we‘ll explore how to use Python to check the temperature of your CPU, GPU, hard drives, and more. We‘ll also cover additional tricks like controlling fan speeds, getting battery info, and monitoring overall system resource usage.\\n\\nWhether you‘re looking to keep tabs on your computer‘s vitals or make your Python scripts hardware-aware, read on to learn all the details!\\n## Checking CPU Temperature\\n\\nKeeping your CPU operating at safe temperatures is crucial for system stability and longevity. Python makes it easy to monitor your CPU temp so you can take action if needed.\\n\\nThe [psutil](https://psutil.readthedocs.io/en/latest/) module contains a `sensors_temperatures()` method that returns a dictionary of hardware component temperatures, including the CPU:\\n\\n```\\nimport psutil\\n\\ntemps = psutil.sensors_temperatures() \\n\\ncpu_temp = temps[‘coretemp‘][0].current # Get CPU temp\\nprint(f\\\"CPU Temperature: {cpu_temp}°C\\\")\\n```\\n\\nOn my system with an Intel Core i7-9700K, this prints:\\n\\n```\\nCPU Temperature: 45.5°C\\n```\\n\\nYou can see the current CPU temperature in Celsius. Values up to about 60-70°C are generally safe under load, but you‘ll want to keep an eye on it if the temp rises further. If it exceeds 90-100°C, thermal throttling will kick in which can severely impact performance.\\n\\nChart showing impact of thermal throttling\\n_Thermal throttling due to high CPU temperatures can significantly reduce clock speeds. (Source: Intel)_\\n\\nFor advanced usage, you could log CPU temperatures over time to visualize heat trends and check for abnormal spikes:\\n\\n```\\nimport psutil\\nfrom datetime import datetime\\nimport time\\n\\nlog_interval = 5 # seconds\\n\\nwhile True:\\n    temps = psutil.sensors_temperatures()\\n\\n    with open(\\\"cpu_temp_log.csv\\\", \\\"a\\\") as log:  \\n        log.write(f\\\"{datetime.now()}, {temps[‘coretemp‘][0].current}\\\\n\\\")\\n\\n    time.sleep(log_interval)\\n```\\n\\nThis will log the CPU temp every 5 seconds, allowing you to better monitor usage patterns. You can also have a Python script trigger notifications if a temperature threshold is exceeded.\\n\\nAdditionally, keeping historical temperature data allows you to correlate performance issues with spikes in CPU temp.\\n\\n## Reading GPU Temperature\\n\\nIf your computer has a dedicated graphics card, checking its temp can also be useful.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://powershellcommands.com/powershell-cpu-temperature\",\n      \"title\": \"Check CPU Temperature Using PowerShell Commands\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"logo Powershell Commands\\n\\n* Shop\\n* Categories\\n* About Us\\n* Support\\n\\nEnable dark mode \\n\\nEnable dark mode\\n\\nAdvanced\\n\\n# Check CPU Temperature Using PowerShell Commands\\n\\nDiscover how to monitor your Powershell CPU temperature effortlessly. This guide unveils concise commands for quick performance insights.\\n\\n170\\n\\nCheck CPU Temperature Using PowerShell Commands\\n\\nTo retrieve the CPU temperature using PowerShell, you can utilize the `Get-WmiObject` command to query the thermal zone data from the Win32\\\\_TemperatureProbe class. Here's a simple code snippet to get you started:\\n\\n```\\nGet-WmiObject -Namespace root\\\\wmi -Class MSAcpi_ThermalZone | Select-Object -Property CurrentTemperature\\n```\\n\\nThis command will return the current temperature of your CPU in tenths of degrees Kelvin.\\n\\n## Understanding CPU Temperature\\n\\n### What is CPU Temperature?\\n\\nCPU temperature refers to the heat generated by the processor during operation.\\nUnderstanding this temperature is crucial because it directly impacts the performance of your computer. Most CPUs have an _optimal operating temperature range_ . Operating outside this range can lead to performance throttling or even permanent damage.\\n\\n### Impact of High CPU Temperature\\n\\nWhen the CPU operates at elevated temperatures, several adverse effects can occur.\\n\\n* **Performance Issues** : High temperatures can cause the CPU to throttle its performance, meaning it runs slower to prevent damage.\\n* **Risk of Overheating** : Prolonged high temperatures may lead to hardware malfunctions or failure.\\n* **System Instability** : Crashes and unexpected behavior become more prevalent in systems where the CPU is consistently overheating.\\n\\nTherefore, regular monitoring of CPU temperature is essential for maintaining system health and performance.\\n\\nMastering the PowerShell Enumerator: A Quick Guide Mastering the PowerShell Enumerator: A Quick Guide\\n## Setting Up PowerShell for CPU Monitoring\\n\\n### Prerequisites\\n\\nBefore you can monitor CPU temperature, ensure that **PowerShell** is installed on your system. Additionally, you may need administrative permissions to access certain system information.\\n\\n### Installing Necessary Tools\\n\\n#### Using PowerShell Modules\\n\\nPowerShell supports various modules that facilitate obtaining hardware information, including CPU temperature measurements. One such recommended module is **OpenHardwareMonitor** .\\n\\n#### Example: Installing OpenHardwareMonitor Module\\n\\nTo install the module, run the following command in PowerShell:\\n\\n```\\nInstall-Module -Name OpenHardwareMonitor\\n```\\n\\nThis simple command will enable you to access the necessary functionalities for monitoring hardware metrics including CPU temperature.\\n\\nUnderstanding the PowerShell Or Operator with Ease Understanding the PowerShell Or Operator with Ease\\n\\n## Accessing CPU Temperature Data\\n\\n### Using WMI (Windows Management Instrumentation)\\n\\n...\\n\\n### Mastering PowerShell Filter Operators for Quick Results\\n\\n110\\n\\nfeatured \\n\\n Basics\\n\\n2024-09-03T05:00:00\\n\\n### Mastering the PowerShell -Like Operator with Ease\\n\\n50\\n\\nNever Miss A Post! 🎉\\n\\n* 01 Get membership discounts\\n* 02 Be the first to know about new guides and scripts\\n\\nsubsc\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.techepages.com/get-cpu-temperature-using-powershell/\",\n      \"title\": \"Find CPU temperature using Powershell - TECHEPAGES\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2025-01-11\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"You can use a Powershell script or function to get the temperature values of the CPU in Celsius directly. The function below will bring out the three temperature values of CPU temperature in Celsius.\\n\\nfunction Get-Temperature {  \\n$t = Get-WmiObject MSAcpi\\\\_ThermalZoneTemperature -Namespace “root/wmi”  \\n$returntemp = @()\\n\\nforeach ($temp in $t.CurrentTemperature) { $currentTempKelvin = $temp / 10 $currentTempCelsius = $currentTempKelvin – 273.15 $currentTempFahrenheit = (9/5) \\\\* $currentTempCelsius + 32 $returntemp += $currentTempCelsius.ToString() + ” C : ” + $currentTempFahrenheit.ToString() + ” F : ” + $currentTempKelvin + “K” } return $returntemp\\n\\n}\\n\\nGet-Temperature\\n\\nYou can use this function on the Powershell prompt. Or, you can save it as a PS file and execute it on the system.\\n\\nI chose to put the function on the Powershell prompt directly and got the temperature values in Kelvin, Fahrenheit, and Celsius as displayed in the command output screenshot below.\\nCPU temperature in Celsius using Powershell\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nBoth these methods shared above will help you fetch the CPU temperature of a local or remote computer using Powershell. You can use these cmdlets on Windows 11, Windows 10, and Windows servers as well.\\n\\nThe good thing about getting temperature values through Powershell is that we do not need to install any third-party applications on your desktop or servers.\\n\\nRajesh Dhawan\\n\\n[Rajesh Dhawan](https://www.techepages.com/author/techepages_admin/)\\n\\nSimplifying technology, one step at a time.\\n\\n[](https://www.linkedin.com/in/rajesh-dhawan-27151b5/ \\\"Linkedin\\\")\\n\\nCategories [PowerShell](https://www.techepages.com/category/powershell/)\\n\\n[Get all hotfixes installed by date in Powershell](https://www.techepages.com/get-all-hotfixes-installed-by-date-in-powershell/)\\n\\n[How to check the Windows Update history in Windows 11?](https://www.techepages.com/how-to-check-the-windows-update-history-in-windows-11/)\\n\\n#### **Important Pages**\\n* [Free ESU for Windows 10 in Europe](https://www.techepages.com/free-windows-10-extended-security-updates-for-european-customers/)\\n* [Extended Security Updates for Windows 10](https://www.techepages.com/extended-security-updates-esu-for-windows-10/)\\n* Price information of Windows 10 ESU\\n* [Exchange Server 2019 - End of Life Date](https://www.techepages.com/microsoft-exchange-server-2019-end-of-life-update/)\\n* Windows Server 2016 - End of Life Date\\n* Windows 11 - OEM vs Retail Licenses\\n* Windows 10 End of Life\\n\\n## Windows 11 Intel Compati\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.trishtech.com/2024/05/how-to-find-cpu-temperature-with-powershell-on-windows\",\n      \"title\": \"How to Find CPU Temperature with PowerShell on Windows\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Please wait while your request is being verified...\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.w3tutorials.net/blog/get-cpu-temperature-in-cmd-power-shell/\",\n      \"title\": \"How to Get CPU Temperature in Windows CMD/PowerShell: Fix ...\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2026-01-16\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"In this guide, we’ll explore step-by-step methods to check CPU temperature using CMD and PowerShell, explain why the \\\"Not Supported\\\" error happens, and provide fixes to resolve it.\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"warnings\": null,\n  \"usage\": [\n    {\n      \"name\": \"sku_search\",\n      \"count\": 1\n    }\n  ],\n  \"session_id\": \"ses_0d4353dccffeI9tkgNAMHqAo4e\"\n}",
